<HEADLINE>
FT  10 AUG 94 / Walker 'denied Pounds 7.5m transfer'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr George Walker, former chief executive of Brent Walker, denied to police
that he had ever stolen money from the property and leisure group, an Old
Bailey jury heard yes-terday.
He also denied authorising the transfer of Pounds 7.5m from the company, in
spite of his signature's appearance on documentation for the transaction,
the court was told.
Mr Walker and Mr Wilfred Aquilina, the company's former finance director,
are accused of fraudulently boosting the profits of Brent Walker by some
Pounds 19m. They deny charges of theft, false accounting and conspiracy to
falsify accounts.
The prosecution alleges the profits were boosted by bogus transactions
carried out within the group's film division. It claims the Brent Walker
group in effect funded its own profits, and that the bogus transactions were
disguised through a circular money trail.
The jury was read the transcripts of interviews Mr Walker had with police
attached to the Serious Fraud Office in April 1992 before his arrest in
January 1993.
Mr Walker was questioned about the transfer of Pounds 7.5m from Brent Walker
to the Arab Bank Corporation in New York in May 1989. The prosecution
alleges this payment was part of the circular money trail used to boost the
profits.
Mr Walker agreed that a document concerning the transfer bore what appeared
to be his signature, but denied having authorised the payment.
Although he did not accuse anyone of forgery, Mr Walker told police he would
never have sent such a letter, which was written on paper that had not come
from his office.
Police officers put it to him that the Pounds 7.5m had been stolen from
Brent Walker.
Mr Walker replied: 'I have never had a penny out of Brent Walker. I never
touched this money ever. That is a fact.'
If money had been stolen from the company, he added, then nobody would help
the police more than himself.
Mr Walker said it was often his practice to sign papers without reading
them. He trusted fellow directors to have done their job properly. Had he
questioned everything they did, he would never have had the time to to build
up the company, he said.
The trial continues today.
</TEXT>
