<HEADLINE>
FT  10 AUG 94 / Long hot summer hinders crops
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON MAITLAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The long hot summer has produced an earlier harvest than usual in many parts
of the country, but the lack of rain is pushing yields down in some areas,
the National Farmers' Union said yesterday, Alison Maitland writes. The
sunshine has ripened the cereal crop up to two weeks early, said Mr John
Malcolm, the union's chief economist, but the shortage of rain, especially
in the south and south-west of England, means that the ears of corn have not
swelled out fully. Combined with poorer soil quality, this has left areas
such as the Cotswolds and Chilterns reporting yields as low as 4 tonnes a
hectare compared with a national average of 5.5 tonnes in a normal year. But
fortunate farmers in parts of East Anglia, England's bread basket, are
reporting yields as high as 10 tonnes a hectare. Mr Malcolm said this was
thanks either to well-timed cloudbursts during the past month or to farmers'
decisions to irrigate.
Commodities, Page 24
</TEXT>
