<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WARSAW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Poland's privately-owned PolSat TV plans to continue transmission despite a
Supreme Administrative Court (NSA) ruling suspending its licence for
nationwide broadcasting, a PolSat official said yesterday. The court made
the decision on Friday at a closed session, citing numerous legal challenges
the station faced. The National Radio and TV Council, Poland's broadcasting
authority, suggested the ruling infringed its responsibility and said it
licence to PolSat in January, rejecting bids from from several
foreign-Polish media groups. It said it preferred PolSat because it was
fully Polish-owned. However, the challengers said they had been offering
better programming and had sounder financial foundations. Among PolSat's
critics was President Lech Walesa, who reportedly tried to remove the
chairman of the broadcasting council for giving the licence to the station.
