FT  10 AUG 94 / Russian private employment up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By AP
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
More than half Russia's workers are now employed in the private sector as
the country continues to develop a market economy, the government said
yesterday. The latest report from the state statistics committee did not say
exactly what share of the economy is now in private hands, but it said
Russia now has nearly 1m small businesses employing 9m people. A majority of
workers are now employed in the private sector and 70 per cent of
state-controlled industry has been turned over to private owners since
market reforms began in 1992, it said. Two-thirds of these privatised
enterprises are profitable, it is claimed.
