<HEADLINE>
FT  10 AUG 94 / Package holiday industry set to escape monopolies probe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER, Leisure Industries Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Office of Fair Trading is expected to announce this week that it will
not refer the package holiday industry to the Monopolies and Mergers
Commission.
The announcement will follow a 13-month OFT inquiry into complaints by small
travel companies that they were finding it difficult to get on to travel
retailers' shelves. Independent companies said they were being hampered by
the strong links between the biggest tour operators and travel agents.
The OFT also investigated the large tour operators' practice of giving
travel agent staff financial incentives to sell their holidays. The OFT is
thought to have concluded, however, that there is no need for further
inquiries by the MMC.
The expected announcement will be welcomed by Thomson and Airtours, the two
largest travel groups, which have argued that the industry is highly
competitive, selling foreign holidays to an increasing number of consumers
at low prices.
Independent operators are hoping that, in the absence of a referral to the
commission, the OFT asks large groups for undertakings to treat smaller
companies fairly.
Thomson owns Lunn Poly, the largest travel retail chain. Airtours owns Going
Places, the second largest. The two retail chains are currently engaged in a
price-cutting skirmish, selling summer 1995 holidays at discounts of up to
15 per cent.
Lunn Poly has argued that far from using its market dominance to drive up
prices and deprive consumers of choice, the cost of foreign holidays had
actually fallen over the past year. It said the average price of a summer
holiday booked by Lunn Poly by the end of June this year was Pounds 353,
compared with Pounds 356 last year.
Lunn Poly said last week that it currently sells the holidays of 147 travel
suppliers. The three largest operators - Thomson, Airtours and Owners Abroad
 -are given only 33 per cent of the racking space in the Lunn Poly shops. It
said the remaining space was occupied by brochures from travel suppliers who
account for only 30 per cent of sales.
It added: 'Far from being undersupported, small tour operators are allocated
far more shelf space than their proportion of sales would justify.'
Small tour operators have argued, however, that large travel retailers
demand higher commissions from them than from leading operators.
Thomson buys into UK market, Page 17
</TEXT>
