<HEADLINE>
FT  09 AUG 94 / Murdoch warms to Blair
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Rupert Murdoch, chairman and chief executive of News Corporation, said
last night he 'could imagine' supporting Mr Tony Blair, the Labour leader.
Mr Murdoch said in an interview with the German magazine Der Spiegel that
although he was a conservative, his newspapers had supported Lord Wilson,
the former Labour prime minister, and many Labor politicians in Australia.
'I could even imagine supporting the British Labour leader Tony Blair,' he
said.
Mr Murdoch's company owns five UK national newspapers and a majority stake
in BSkyB, the satellite TV network in which Pearson, owner of the Financial
Times has a stake.
Mr David Blunkett, Labour party chairman, said last night: 'I think there
has been a very clear change in the attitude of the Murdoch press anyway
over the last two years, with their virulent attacks on John Major.'
But Mr John Maples, deputy Tory party chairman, said: 'He only said he could
imagine doing it. He did not say he was going to do it, and it would be very
odd if he did.'
</TEXT>
