<HEADLINE>
FT  09 AUG 94 / London Stock Exchange: Reckitt off on buy talk
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVE THOMPSON, CHRISTOPHER PRICE, PETER JOHN and JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Household products group Reckitt &amp; Colman slid on speculation that it was
poised to buy Eastman Kodak's household products division for between
Dollars 1.7bn and Dollars 2bn.
Reckitt ended the day down 7 at 614p as analysts wondered how the company
would get hold of the necessary cash and decided that a tap on shareholders
was the only way.
However, Lehman Brothers argued that Reckitt was an unlikely candidate and
that global rivals Colgate-Palmolive, Unilever and Procter &amp; Gamble were
more plausible buyers.
Ms Jo Walton, Lehman's pharmaceuticals analyst, said the company would be
able to service additional debt of only Dollars 1.55bn. She said it was more
likely that the company could buy some lines of Kodak's Stirling Winthrop
arm that might provide a good fit.
Meanwhile, Unilever, which reports second-quarter figures on Friday,
strengthened 14 to 1081p. The Anglo-Dutch group is expected to announce
profits of between Pounds 550m and Pounds 590m.
