<HEADLINE>
FT  09 AUG 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Bond yields offer modest
boost to Dow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US share prices edged higher yesterday in quiet trading as an early decline
in bond yields provided a modest boost to stock market sentiment, writes
Patrick Harverson in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 6.79 up at 3,753.81 and the
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 firmed 0.80 to 457.89, while the Nasdaq composite
gained 1.80 at 720.47. New York SE trading volume was low at 217.7m shares.
After last week's late sell-off that was prompted by a surge in bond yields,
trading was expected to be subdued yesterday. Bond yields had risen on
Friday because a stronger than expected July jobs report had raised fears
that the Federal Reserve would tighten interest rates again to slow down the
economy.
When bond yields opened lower in the morning, it provided a lift to
equities. A slight firming in the dollar also supported stocks initially but
trading activity remained light, with many investors and dealers choosing to
stay on the sidelines until later in the week, when July inflation figures
are due to be released. Prices, however, held their ground in the face of an
upturn in bond yields later in the day.
Leading issues were mostly firmer, although gains were kept to a minimum.
General Motors was ahead Dollars  1/8 at Dollars 50 3/8 , IBM Dollars 7/8 at
Dollars 63 3/8 and Merck Dollars 5/8 at Dollars 30 1/2.
North American Mortgage forged ahead Dollars 3 to Dollars 30 5/8 in heavy
trading after the mortgage banking company revealed that it had asked Morgan
Stanley to advise on strategic alternatives to enhance shareholder value.
Molecular Biosystems jumped Dollars 2 1/2 to Dollars 12 3/8 after the US
Food and Drug Administration gave final approval for Albunex, the company's
flagship product used as a contrast-imaging agent.
Canada
Toronto stocks ended mixed in moderate trading after a strong showing by the
Canadian dollar and bonds failed to carry over to the equity markets.
The TSE 300 index gained 6.8 at 4,175.4, but declines outscored rises by 365
to 309. Volume was 53.3m shares.
Canadian bonds and currency surged after the release of a survey in Quebec
that showed weakening support for the separatist Parti Quebecois in the
upcoming provincial election.
Venezuela
Equities in Caracas showed little reaction to reports that a further crisis
in the financial sector could be developing following the suspension from
trading of four of the country's banks. The Merinvest composite index closed
1.24, or 1 per cent, down at 124.58.
The stock exchange authorities later lifted the suspension from two of the
banks. Mr Julio Sosa Rodriguez, the country's finance minister, denied that
there was a problem in the banking sector, but added that there could be
changes to the boards of directors in some of the banks.
Among major stocks, Electricidad de Caracas was down 5 bolivars at 300
bolivars.
</TEXT>
