<HEADLINE>
FT  09 AUG 94 / Government Bonds: Treasuries little changed ahead of Dollars
40bn refunding
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON and ANTONIA SHARPE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US Treasury prices were little changed across the maturity range yesterday
as dealers and investors prepared for this week's Dollars 40bn quarterly
refunding auctions.
In late trading, the benchmark 30-year government bond was up  1/16 at 84
29/32 , yielding 7.532 per cent.
The two-year note was also slightly firmer, up  1/32 at 99 27/32 , to yield
6.192 per cent.
Trading activity was very light from the opening, with participants
reluctant to commit funds to the market ahead of the refunding round.
The auctions begin today with the sale of Dollars 17bn in three-year notes.
That will be followed by auctions of Dollars 12bn in 10-year notes tomorrow
and Dollars 11bn in 30-year bonds on Thursday.
Last week's strong July employment report raised fears in the bond market
that the Federal Reserve will once again raise interest rates to slow the
economy, and the talk of another monetary policy tightening has only made
dealers and investors even more cautious than usual in the planning of their
strategies for the Treasury auctions.
European government bond markets were quiet as investors focused on this
week's US refunding. In the absence of meaningful investor activity, the
market continued its debate on whether Germany would continue to cut
interest rates in the wake of buoyant economic data.
Salomon Brothers took the view that the strong German recovery could mean
that the Bundesbank would not cut rates further in this cycle, turning its
attention instead to inflation worries.
However, Kidder Peabody Securities said the Bundesbank was likely to cut
interest rates after Germany's federal elections in October.
On Liffe, the September contract of the bund future traded in a narrow range
before easing 0.34 to 93.07 in the late afternoon in meagre volume of 58,000
lots.
Dealers noted that a widening in the yield spread between UK gilts and
bunds, which reached 175 basis points on Friday, prompted some switching
from bunds to gilts. This caused the spread to tighten again to 158 basis
points.
Gilts rose on the release of weaker than forecast producer prices data for
July but, surprisingly, shrugged off a big rise in consumer credit for June.
Mr Simon Briscoe of S. G. Warburg said the Bank of England was likely to
interpret the lending data as a clear indication that the economy was still
growing fast and that it would be that bit keener to raise rates soon.
In the meantime, news that the Bank was raising Pounds 700m through four
taps of existing bonds strengthened the view that it would not be holding an
auction this month.
On Liffe, the September long gilt future stood  5/16 higher at 102 5/8 in
the late afternoon in small volume of 31,200 lots.
</TEXT>
