<HEADLINE>
FT  09 AUG 94 / International Company News: Charter stands by bid for Esab
after shares rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Charter, the UK industrial group, said yesterday it stood by its bid for
Esab, in spite of a further rise in the Swedish welding group's shares above
the offer price following a sharp upgrade in the company's profits forecast.
Esab shares rose to SKr355, SKr10 ahead of Charter's Pounds 260m (Dollars
400m) recommended June bid, after it announced a surge in half-year profits
after financial items to SKr195m (Dollars 25.19m), compared with SKr23m in
the same period last year.
The Gothenburg-based group, the world's largest supplier of welding
equipment, added that it expected full-year profits of about SKr390m, well
ahead of its previous forecast of SKr320m. It said income targets set for
the coming few years would be reached earlier than expected.
The results fuelled speculation in Stockholm that Charter, which already
holds 53 per cent of Esab, might fail in its target of capturing 90 per cent
by the deadline of this Friday. Several Swedish institutions that hold the
bulk of the outstanding shares have yet to make up their minds and have made
clear they are closely examining claims that the Charter bid undervalues
Esab.
But Mr Charles Parker, Charter commercial director, said yesterday that the
UK company regarded the latest rise in Esab's share price as a blatant
attempt to force it into increasing the bid price. He said the fundamental
assessments which led to the offer at SKr345 - at the time a 20 per cent
premium - had not changed. 'The offer stands as it is,' he said.
Esab attributed the dramatic turnround to a cost-cutting programme which
during the past two years has seen the workforce fall by some 1,700 to just
over 7,000 at the end of June.
Group sales in the first six months rose to SKr3.74bn from SKr3.38bn as
demand in Esab's main markets in Europe remained slack. Operating profits
after depreciation grew to SKr222m from SKr93m. Return on capital in the
year to June was 13.7 per cent, compared with 9.1 per cent in 1993.
Mr Lars Westerberg, chief executive, said he expected that sales growth
would continue, sustaining profits growth.
</TEXT>
