<HEADLINE>
FT  09 AUG 94 / Saatchi claims PC status as profits leap 68%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Marketing Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Maurice Saatchi declared the Saatchi &amp; Saatchi advertising group a '100
per cent politically correct organisation' yesterday, as the group announced
higher than expected interim pre-tax profits of Pounds 15.3m, up 68 per cent
on the previous Pounds 9.1m.
The 'politically correct' status claimed by Mr Saatchi, chairman, comes from
the fact that the group now has no one on a contract longer than three
years. At the annual meeting in June, Mr Saatchi renounced his five-year
rolling contract, worth Pounds 625,000 a year, and moved to a three-year
fixed-term contract at a base salary of Pounds 200,000. Bonuses will be
linked to revenue growth.
The semi-public row between Mr Saatchi and Mr Charlie Scott, chief
executive, over the management of the organisation, appears to have
subsided, with Mr Saatchi yesterday describing relationships as
'magnificent'. Mr Scott agreed: 'I have worse arguments with my wife than I
do with Maurice, and I've only been married four weeks.'
Mr Scott described the volume and quality of new business wins this year as
the best since he joined the group at the beginning of 1990. The impact of
the new accounts, which include the National Lottery, Compaq Computer and
Qantas, are not expected to feed through until 1995.
The share price leapt 15p to close at 176p.
Turnover slipped 6.1 per cent to Pounds 379.4m (Pounds 404.1) in the six
months to June 30. The decline had been expected because of the loss of two
important US accounts, Chrysler and Helene Curtis, together worth Pounds
16.8m in revenue. Other factors were the negative impact of exchange rate
movements, and the fact that businesses were sold.
Operating profits from continuing operations were up 15 per cent to Pounds
21.7m (Pounds 18.9m), following an attack on costs last year. Operating
margins increased from 5.3 to 5.7 per cent and Mr Scott said his target
remained 10 per cent by 1996.
Earnings per share rose 53 per cent to 2.9p (1.9p). No dividend will be paid
 -Mr Saatchi and Mr Scott said the position on dividends would be kept under
review.
Ms Lorna Tilbian, media analyst with SG Warburg Securities, said yesterday
that Saatchi had 'certainly turned the corner'. She is forecasting full-year
pre-tax profits of Pounds 30m and earnings per share of 5.7p.
</TEXT>
