<HEADLINE>
FT  09 AUG 94 / BA fails to impress City with 40% rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British Airways yesterday reported a 40 per cent increase in pre-tax profit
as passenger and cargo traffic continued to recover. But the strong
performance failed to impress the stock market with BA shares falling 12p to
close at 417p.
BA's first-quarter profit of Pounds 88m for the three months to June 30 was
up from Pounds 63m a year ago. Turnover for the period rose to Pounds 1.69bn
from Pounds 1.52bn.
Although profits were in line with expectations, they did not match the more
bullish forecasts, which had exceeded Pounds 90m pre-tax. The market's
reaction also reflected continuing worries about BA's Dollars 400m (Pounds
259m) investment in a 24.6 per cent stake in USAir. The sixth largest US
carrier is struggling to win labour concessions to help it return to
profitability.
BA said yesterday it was not close to deciding whether to write off its
USAir stake. But it acknowledged that the current negotiations between USAir
and its unions were not encouraging and would probably drag on into the
autumn.
Sir Colin Marshall, BA's chairman, said he was encouraged by the overall
first-quarter performance. It reflected 'buoyant demand' for passenger and
cargo services, with first and business-class premium traffic reaching an
all-time high.
First-quarter operating profits rose 32.4 per cent to Pounds 143m. Fully
diluted earnings per share were 6.4p, slightly up from last year's 6.3p,
largely due to a higher estimated tax rate and the rights issue of June
1993.
A total of 8.3m people flew on the airline's scheduled and charter flights
in the first quarter. Passenger traffic increased by 6.9 per cent on
scheduled services.
The biggest improvement was in the high-yield first and business class
traffic which rose by 12 per cent, double the rate of economy class traffic.
This helped passenger yields on scheduled services to rise by 3.4 per cent.
Cargo traffic rose by nearly 20 per cent with a total of 171,000 tonnes
carried.
BA also said net borrowings fell by Pounds 201m in the first quarter, taking
its gearing to 56.9 per cent - a 2.7 percentage point improvement since the
end of March.
Lex, Page 16
</TEXT>
