<HEADLINE>
FT  09 AUG 94 / Price of car parts may rise under Brussels proposals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
European car owners may be forced to pay higher prices for spare parts and
be banned from shopping around for better deals under European Commission
proposals to harmonise rules governing the legal protection of industrial
design.
The Commission's plans will insist that certain car body parts be legally
protected for the first three years after a car is launched, giving the
manufacturers the exclusive right to supply spares during that period.
Consumers and independent suppliers fear the proposals will stifle
competition and allow car manufacturers to charge what they wish for
windscreens, panels, headlamps and other parts.
The UK has a free market in the supply of spare parts for repairs. This
contrasts with countries such as France, which uses copyright law to protect
carmakers from the competition of independent suppliers.
The Commission, under pressure from powerful carmakers on one side, and
consumer groups and independent suppliers on the other, has come up with the
three-year compromise plan as part of a wider initiative to harmonise rules
covering the legal protection of industrial design.
These rules differ greatly across the 12 EU member states.
In the proposals, the Commission argues that many car parts, such as
windscreens, are unlikely to qualify for legal protection according to
strict rules defining design and that consumer groups are overestimating the
costs of such protection.
No final decision has been taken on the Commission's proposals. They are
being scrutinised by the working group of the Council of Ministers and have
yet to be debated by the European Parliament.
However, independent suppliers believe manufacturers could use the
three-year ruling to create a monopoly in the supply of spare parts.
'Without a repair right, the availability of spare parts would decrease, the
price of spare parts would increase, and the very existence of the European
independent spare parts industry would be put at risk,' says the European
Campaign for an Automotive Repair Right, a grouping of independent suppliers
and consumer organisations.
They also argue that the ruling could cause great inconvenience to consumers
in the UK who are able to ring up glass suppliers, for example, 24 hours a
day for repairs on broken windscreens.
'It is not just a matter of cost, it is a matter of flexibility,' said Mr
David Roycroft, of Pilkington, the UK glass manufacturer.
The carmakers say they should be allowed some sort of protection for parts
in order to recoup the costs of investment in design, although the consumer
groups say those costs are covered in the sale of the vehicle.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
