<HEADLINE>
FT  09 AUG 94 / The Lex Column: UK property
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The long queue of investors for Pillar's flotation says more about the
company than the state of the wider property market. Despite the brightening
economic prospects, there is still little sign of rising rents. The latest
survey evidence points to falling capital values in retail, office and
industrial sectors. Anecdotal evidence suggests institutional investors
pulled back from direct investment in property during the second quarter.
This may have been caused by falling equity and bond markets, which tended
to push property weightings higher even without action. Pension funds may
also be mulling the government's proposed solvency test and asking where
property might fit into their portfolios in future.
There seems little chance of another slide in values, especially now that
the gilts market has recovered some poise. With property values becalmed,
though, stock market investors are looking for companies which can add value
to their assets through development or trading. Pillar seems to fit the bill
 -as did Argent, which saw its flotation oversubscribed in June. At a 5 per
cent discount to net assets neither flotation was especially cheap. Indeed,
if Pillar and Argent represent fair value at this level it is difficult to
see why the less dynamic or well-placed property companies are trading at a
similar discount.
</TEXT>
