<HEADLINE>
FT  09 AUG 94 / The Lex Column: UK economy
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Yesterday's economic data leave the debate about UK inflation as confused as
ever. Input prices are growing faster than output prices, although an annual
rate of 2.9 per cent hardly amounts to hyper-inflation. Consumer borrowing
is up sharply on a net basis, though a large part of the jump seems to
reflect a slowdown in repayments. Gross lending in June scarcely rose at all
and gross lending on credit cards actually fell. Taken together the figures
can thus be construed as offering comfort both to those who argue that
inflationary pressures are building up in the economy and to those who claim
that price pressures are likely to remain muted.
Yet it would be naive to assume that the economy can continue growing as
fast as it is without inflation eventually accelerating again. For the time
being higher volumes will continue to offset the impact of raw material
price increases on unit costs. The slowdown in credit repayment could be a
sign that April's tax rises are hurting consumers. While wage rises remain
restrained, they are likely to remain price conscious. But if the
authorities wait till wage pressure returns, it will be too late for a
pre-emptive strike.
</TEXT>
