<PROFILE>_AN-EHIE8AC7FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940809
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  09 AUG 94 / The Lex Column: Smith's short sight
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Even by the standards of 1988, when countless companies struck deals their
shareholders lived to regret, Smith &amp; Nephew's acquisition of Ioptex was an
expensive blunder. At the exchange rates then prevailing it paid Pounds 140m
for a company that is now being sold for just Pounds 11m. After writing-down
the company's assets, there is a total loss of Pounds 148m which represents
almost three years' dividends and a third of shareholders' funds.
In retrospect the acquisition was breathtakingly risky. Smith &amp; Nephew paid
over five times annual sales for the number four player in a market that was
fast going ex-growth. The deal was so structured that despite the high price
the acquisition would not dilute earnings in the first year. Maybe the
ingenuity of the financial engineering blinded management to the dangers.
They should certainly have questioned whether margins approaching 45 per
cent were sustainable in a mature US market, or whether Smith could add
anything to Ioptex's attempts to expand internationally. It was dismissing
the regulatory threat that was to prove most damaging, since the price
controls placed on some lenses by the US authorities 18 months later were a
blow from which Ioptex never really recovered.
Smith stresses that all its other US acquisitions have been successful and
that it has learned hard lessons from Ioptex. If this reassures
shareholders, who have seen dividends rise by just 15 per cent over the past
five years, they may still wonder why over the same period the pay of Smith
&amp; Nephew's successive chief executives has doubled.
</TEXT>
