<HEADLINE>
FT  09 AUG 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In Nature Detectives professional camera crews visit some of Britain's
natural history enthusiasts. Today they include David Mossman and Christine
Wagner who swim with grey seals in the North Sea; Derek and Pauline Harrison
who attempt at their Lake District hotel to feed red squirrels and not grey;
and businessman Mike Warburg who breeds great crested newts in Chorleywood
(7.00 BBC1). BBC2 investigates the Indian passion for cricket in A Whole
Different Ball Game and shows that the game affects and is affected by all
aspects of life: political, religious and social (7.40 BBC2). Subject of the
last in BBC2's Heretic series, looking at men whose radical ideas have led
to their being ostracised, is Eric Laithwaite, former Professor of
Electrical Engineering at Imperial College. His heresy is a belief in
gyroscopic propulsion which appears to challenge Newton's laws. Last month
he patented a new device which he believes will make his name (10.00). Billy
Connolly's World Tour Of Scotland splendidly combines stage act and fond
travelogue (10.25 BBC1).
