<HEADLINE>
FT  09 AUG 94 / People: Strategic move for London Stock Exchange
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The London Stock Exchange, once the English gentleman's bastion, has
appointed an American woman, Fields Wicker-Miurin, 36, to the newly created
post of director of strategy and finance.
The Exchange is facing increasing competition both at home - from
alternative trading systems - and abroad - from other exchanges which are
increasingly challenging London's role as the centre of cross-border
share-trading. Mike Lawrence, the chief executive, created the position as
part of a wide-ranging shake-up at the Exchange and the executive has spent
six months seeking a suitable candidate.
'The main challenge is to make sure we can maintain our leading position in
European and global securities markets,' Wicker-Miurin says, describing her
new job.
For Lawrence, described by the City's old guard as 'not one of us', the
appointment may be a bit of a gamble, although Wicker-Miurin's credentials
are impeccable.
A native of North Carolina with an MA in international economics and
European studies from Johns Hopkins University, Wicker-Miurin also studied
at the Institute d'Etudes Politiques in Paris. She has lived and worked in
Europe since February 1987, when she was sent to Luxembourg by Core States
Financial, a large regional bank then known as Philadelphia National Bank,
to establish a European operation.
At that time, like many big US commercial banks, Core States Financial had
aspirations to use its banking relationships to build a distribution base
for commercial paper and other types of securities. However, Core States,
along with many of its competitors, found the strategy wrong and the bank
withdrew.
But Wicker-Miurin stayed, and signed on as a strategy consultant with
Strategic Planning Consultants, now part of Mercer Management Consultants
where her clients were leading UK and international investment banks and
insurance companies.
</TEXT>
