<HEADLINE>
FT  09 AUG 94 / Argument rages over holes in the ground: The wider
implications of Nottinghamshire's quarrying debate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Nottinghamshire is searching for the impossible - an agreement between
industry, politicians, residents and environmentalists on quarrying sand and
gravel.
At county level the outcome of the search will settle the location of big
holes in the ground, the conditions under which they may be dug and how the
land will be reclaimed. All of this will be written in the county council's
minerals local plan.
At national level the search has a wider implication. It reflects the
environmental price which has to be paid for economic development.
The competing parties are polishing their arguments for a public inquiry in
October. The arguments will swirl around the proposals of the county
council, embodied in a draft minerals plan. The council is the planning
authority for minerals, granting or refusing permission for quarries. It is
trying to settle what will be worked during the next 10 years, and where.
It is a testing role because Nottinghamshire has extensive mineral
resources, and the greater the desire to exploit them, the more acute the
tensions. The main deposits of sand and gravel - which are vital raw
materials for the construction industry - are in the Trent and Idle valleys.
Nearly all recent extraction, running at 2.5m to 3m tonnes a year from 10
big and several small quarries, has been confined to these valleys.
Quarrying companies are drawn to the county's deposits because they offer
high yields and hard material, meeting most specifications for concrete. As
the draft plan noted: 'This factor can give Nottinghamshire's deposits a
premium above those found elsewhere.'
The county council draws its authority to settle which deposits will be
worked from the Town and Country Planning Act 1990. But the council is
caught between its own voters, who would tend to wish all quarries were
elsewhere, and instructions from Whitehall that control the tonnage of
aggregates to be mined.
The Department of the Environment has a national co-ordinating group of
officials and industry executives which looks at aggregates supply and
demand, and forecasts future needs. This group gets its information from
regional committees, which in turn tell the counties what they expect each
should produce.
For Nottinghamshire County Council the key group is the East Midlands
Regional Aggregates Working Party.
Based on the calculations of this government-industry working party, which
itself has been influenced by national forecasts of rising demand,
Nottinghamshire council has been planning for annual production of 3.2m to
3.4m tonnes. Too little, argues the industry. Too much, say local groups
such as parish councils with quarries in their midst, and national
environmental groups such as the Council for the Protection of Rural
England.
Nottinghamshire can meet the rising demand at least until the end of the
century. But the county council hopes to be let off the hook. By the end of
the century, it said, 'it is hoped that government guidance will have
successfully promoted the fundamental changes in supply and demand need, if
an environmental crisis is to be avoided'.
The government has eased the political pressure. It decided, in a planning
guidance note to mineral planning authorities, that it would not be
necessary to make provision for 10 years of aggregates extraction. Seven
years would be enough.
This had two effects. First, it meant that Nottinghamshire could largely
meet expected production levels for seven years from existing quarries,
although some would open up adjacent workings. It avoided any need to make
provision for the opening of a new quarry at Stapleford Woods.
Wimpey Minerals, in the face of spirited opposition from the Stapleford Wood
Action Group, local MPs and the district council, has for more than a year
been looking at the environmental implications of a quarry on Forestry
Commission land near Newark, on the Lincolnshire border.
That struggle has faded away. Mr Des Whicher, secretary of the action group,
said: 'Wimpey thinks we'll go away more quickly than they'll go away. And
they're probably right in that. Local people think the campaign is won.'
Second, the government decision has served to switch local discussion away
from new quarries to issues such as reclamation after quarrying.
For example, at Hoveringham, south west of Newark, where Tarmac Quarry
Products has the biggest quarry in the county, there are fears about the use
of holes for waste tips.
There are worries at Collingham, on the Trent north of Newark, about the
spread of water areas as former quarries become lakes.
Such local argument is part of a wider national debate about the use of
mineral resources and the abuse of nature that sometimes implies.
For industry there is a demand which has to be met - economic development
needs construction materials. Mr Val Shields, publicity manager at Tarmac
Quarry Products, said: 'The needs don't go away and the customers - society
at large - who want things built would have to be satisfied elsewhere,
wherever 'elsewhere' is.'
That is too simple for environmental groups. Mr Tony Juniper, senior
campaigner of Friends of the Earth, said: 'We must look at ways of
stimulating long-term growth apart from digging holes in the ground.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
