<HEADLINE>
FT  09 AUG 94 / Report on quango trips and expenses released
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Health Promotion Wales, a government quango which offers advice on healthier
lifestyles, yesterday made public a district auditor's report on its former
chief executive's overseas visits and expenses claims.
The quango and its administration has been under intense scrutiny since
Professor John Catford resigned as chief executive in February. South Wales
fraud squad was called in to investigate his expense claims for a number of
foreign trips but the Crown Prosecution Service later decided not to bring
criminal proceedings.
The report concludes that the reason for Prof Catford's attendance on
several trips was unclear. A visit to Brazil appeared to have been
undertaken 'for purely personal reasons'.
Mr Gordon Macdonald, head of professional development, has also been
disciplined over his foreign trips. His contract will not be renewed when it
runs out in October.
Mr John Davies, chairman of Health Promotion Wales, said yesterday: 'We are
doing a thoroughly professional and worthwhile job which the NHS values
highly. We are not a tarnished quango although two individuals have been
tarnished.'
He added that procedures on overseas travel had been changed.
Prof Catford now works for the World Health Organisation as public health
adviser to a number of eastern European countries. He has not commented on
the district auditor's report.
Mr Macdonald said: 'The District Audit Services report cites me as
undertaking 26 international visits between April 1990 and January 1994.
This is inaccurate and misleading. Eight of those journeys were to domestic
destinations within the UK.'
</TEXT>
