<HEADLINE>
FT  09 AUG 94 / Minister opens review of safety for drinkers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A review of the government's guidelines on the consumption of alcohol was
launched yesterday.
Mr John Bowis, junior health minister, said in May that he would be
reviewing the limits below which the consumption of alcohol was considered
unlikely to damage health - 21 units a week for men and 14 units for women.
The move followed research showing that moderate drinkers lived longer than
those who did not drink.
Announcing the inquiry's terms of reference yesterday, Mr Bowis said the
departments of health and transport, the Ministry of Agriculture, and the
Home, Scottish and Welsh offices would be represented in a working party.
This would review scientific and medical evidence on the long-term effects
of drinking alcohol before deciding whether the guidelines should be
modified or qualified.
The guidelines were set by the Royal College of General Practitioners,
Psychiatrists and Physicians in 1987. Recent studies - particularly US
research published in the New England Journal of Medicine last December  -
have suggested moderate drinking can reduce the risk of heart attacks.
The New England study found that people who consumed between one and three
drinks daily were half as likely to be at risk of heart attacks as those who
never drank.
Alcohol Concern, the charity, welcomed the review, which it said would help
end confusion about how much it was safe to drink.
It said 'It is important that the government give their own review a high
level of priority because there are currently some 8m drinking above the
existing recommended levels.'
