<HEADLINE>
FT  09 AUG 94 / Free Trade Hall poised to become hotel
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Manchester's Free Trade Hall, originally the headquarters of the Anti-Corn
Law League and currently the home of the Halle Orchestra, is set to become a
luxury hotel.
The city council, which owns the listed building, said yesterday that it
would be turned into a 290-bedroom hotel, with a four to five-star rating,
in a Pounds 30m development.
Mr Graham Stringer, the council's leader, said: 'This will help to confirm
our status as a major European city.'
Central Manchester Development Corporation has yet to receive a planning
application for the scheme, but has indicated hotel use is acceptable.
The proposed scheme would retain the Italian-style, stone building's famous
facade, and incorporate the statues on the rear elevation. Construction is
expected to start early in 1996 when the Halle moves home to the nearby
Pounds 42m International Concert Hall.
The city council said the Free Trade Hall, built in 1856 on the site of the
Peterloo Massacre, has always been a symbol of Manchester's drive for
enterprise and social reform. It has played a leading role in the city's
cultural, social and political life.
Famous people who have spoken there include Charles Dickens, the explorer HM
Stanley, and politicians such as Disraeli, Gladstone and Winston Churchill.
The council said it had agreed heads of terms with La Sande North West, the
development company. La Sande is at an advanced stage of discussions with
Scotts Hotels Management, the UK subsidiary of Scotts Hospitality, the
leading franchise holder of the Marriott hotel brand in the UK. US-based
Marriotts would run the hotel as part of its UK expansion programme.
Mr Stringer said Manchester needed hotel accommodation of the quality
proposed for the scheme. He said it would bring valuable investment and
jobs, and support the city's bid for the Commonwealth Games to be staged in
the year 2002.
</TEXT>
