<HEADLINE>
FT  09 AUG 94 / Receivers to Astra start action over its downfall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The receivers to Astra, the munitions company connected to the Iraqi
supergun affair, have started legal action against the auditors and merchant
bankers who advised the company on one of the acquisitions that led to its
downfall.
Mr Chris Hughes and Mr Chris Barlow, insolvency partners at Coopers &amp;
Lybrand, have issued writs in the last few days against Stoy Hayward, the
accountancy firm, and Paine Webber, the US-based merchant bank.
The writs pursue the organisations for breach of contract and/or negligence
in respect of advice given to Astra before its acquisition of PRB, the
Belgian munitions company, in 1989.
There are no sums specified in the writs, which are a holding action
designed to beat the six-year statute of limitations after which it is
impossible to bring a case.
The PRB acquisition cost Astra Pounds 22m, and the writs are likely to seek
damages for at least this amount as well as costs and interest.
Paine Webber was the merchant bank advising on the PRB acquisition, and Stoy
 -Astra's auditors - conducted due diligence.
Coopers &amp; Lybrand said the writs would be served in the next four months.
The Joint Disciplinary Scheme, the accountancy profession's highest
regulatory body, started an investigation in May into the role of Stoy
Hayward as Astra's auditor following publication of a Department of Trade
and Industry inspectors' report.
Stoy Hayward said last night it was surprised by the move. It added: 'If the
receivers do decide to proceed, it will be most vigorously defended.'
</TEXT>
