<HEADLINE>
FT  09 AUG 94 / Consumers drawn to June sales
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Net lending to UK consumers hit a monthly record in June but City analysts
and the Treasury held back from proclaiming a new spending boom on the
grounds that the official figures from the Central Statistical Office are
prone to sharp fluctuations.
The unexpected strength of June's figures reflected an increase of net
borrowing on credit cards. But there was widespread agreement that this
reflected action by cost-conscious consumers to take advantage of heavy
price discounting in the June sales.
The CSO announced yesterday that net consumer lending, after repayments,
jumped on a seasonally adjusted basis to a new high of Pounds 683m in June
from Pounds 208m in May and was sharply higher than the Pounds 227m of net
lending in June last year.
The monthly statistics, which exclude mortgages but cover lending by finance
houses, unsecured non-mortgage lending by building societies and loans
through bank credit cards under the Visa and Mastercard systems, showed only
a small increase in new lending to Pounds 5.14bn in June from Pounds 5.12bn
in May.
Although the June net lending figure was sharply higher than the City's
Pounds 375m median forecast, analysts pointed out that consumer-credit
statistics are volatile and, in the case of June, followed a very low figure
for May. The modest increase in new lending also suggested that the growth
in net lending resulted from slower credit repayments rather than heavy new
commitments.
In the three months to June, however, net lending as measured for the
monthly statistics rose to Pounds 1.3bn from Pounds 1.11bn in the first
quarter of the year. Broader quarterly figures, published yesterday, showed
that net lending to consumers was at its highest level for almost five years
in the three months to June.
The quarterly figures showed that net lending increased by Pounds 1.41bn in
the second quarter against Pounds 905m in the first three months of the
year. The quarterly figures include lending by banks on personal accounts,
insurance companies, retailers and lending on all bank credit cards and
charge cards as well as the components of the monthly statistics.
A sharp jump in net credit-card borrowing was common to both sets of
figures. Net lending on bank credit cards, as measured by the monthly
statistics, increased to Pounds 267m in June following a large Pounds 99m
repayment in May. The broader quarterly figures showed an increase in net
credit-card borrowing to Pounds 406m from Pounds 158m in the first quarter.
The monthly figures showed net lending by finance houses increased to Pounds
392m in June from Pounds 304m in May. The broader quarterly figures showed
an increase in net lending by non-banks and by banks on personal accounts to
Pounds 932m in the second quarter from Pounds 746m in the first three months
of the year.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9311 Finance, Taxation, and Monetary Policy.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>STATS  Statistics.
    CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
