<HEADLINE>
FT  09 AUG 94 / NKK sheds 1,300 jobs by transferring staff
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GORDON CRAMB
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NKK, the loss-making Japanese steelmaker, announced yesterday it was
shedding a further 1,300 jobs, but its workforce had no overt reason for
despair. Japan's disavowal of compulsory redundancies means the cuts are to
be made, apart from those who wish to retire, by transferring staff to
affiliates or customers.
When they get there, they will remain NKK employees and, their company
assures them, will continue to draw their present salaries. They comprise
technical workers and white-collar staff who, an NKK official said last
night, need not worry about being forced into an inappropriate job.
'Accountants will be sent to accounting departments,' he averred.
If the main disruption to their lives will be that the beige-clad office to
which they bring their bento (lunchbox) each day is not the one they have
previously known, their experience will be better than most have
encountered.
NKK stands to benefit from the secondment only because of the existence of a
system, administered by the government but funded by the private sector,
which for 20 years has helped smooth the paths of companies which fall on
hard times.
The employment adjustment subsidy scheme is due to pay out a record Y112.7bn
(Pounds 727m) this year to employers in designated industries where sales
have dropped from a year earlier. This allows them to take from the offshoot
to which a worker is seconded whatever modest salary contribution is agreed,
while a central pool pays the larger company up to two-thirds of the wage
bill for staff members it has transferred.
Hundreds of thousands of Japanese workers have been asked by their employers
in the past two recession-hit years to bid farewell to colleagues with whom
they have shared their midday rations of cold-rice-in-cardboard, and to
learn the two-hour route to a different train station.
The reach of the programme has been extended as the domestic economic
downturn endures. It now covers more than a quarter of industrial categories
recognised by the labour ministry, and the overall payout is more than 100
times the level of three years ago.
Most employees who have undergone a transfer to a company with which their
employer has a business relationship, however close, appear to find it less
than edifying. A survey of 335 large and small companies, released last
year, suggested that seven out of 10 secondees departed with no guarantee
they would be able to return to their former workplace once conditions
improved.
At least eight in 10 such workers encountered poorer conditions, such as
longer hours and a reduction in paid holidays, and fewer than a third were
compensated for this by the parent company.
A Kawasaki Steel executive has been quoted in Tokyo as saying: 'In general,
affiliates don't have room to accept workers from their parent companies. We
cannot count on them.' Nor, once they are sent there, can the new staff.
One young computer scientist with a master's degree from the prestigious
Tokyo University, who was hired by a steelmaker because it wanted to
diversify into high technology, now finds himself unproductively pushing
paper at a distant offshoot. He wryly recites his designated task: improving
efficiency for the group.
</TEXT>
