installed capacity of 18,000 TEUs (20ft equivalent unit). The Hyundai group
will have a 15 per cent equity stake, and the DCM Shriram group, 26 per
cent. DCM Shriram Industries, which has interests in sugar, chemicals,
textiles, and leasing, has just begun a Rs1bn modernisation and expansion
programme. Mr Bansi Dhar, DCM Hyundai chairman, said the company would enter
the capital markets in the next two months to raise Rs150m for the project.
The plant is expected to be operational by December.
