<HEADLINE>
FT  08 AUG 94 / Ciba's genetically engineered wheat is first in field
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLIVE COOKSON, Science Editor
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The world's first experimental crop of genetically engineered wheat has been
harvested from a field in the UK.
The success of the trial, carried out by Swiss-owned Ciba Seeds in
Cambridgeshire in the east of England, has enormous implications for
agriculture.
It shows that scientists can alter the characteristics of important cereals
in a reliable way, by giving them genes from other species.
The work is expected to lead within a few years to new wheat varieties with
increased resistance to drought and disease, less requirement for expensive
fertilisers, and other improvements.
Although Ciba was first into the field, several other industrial and
academic laboratories are close behind, including Zeneca Seeds, the John
Innes Centre and the Institute of Arable Crops Research in the UK.
The wheat grown at Great Abington, Cambridgeshire, contains 'marker genes'
of no commercial significance, chosen to prove that foreign genetic
material, DNA, can be passed on predictably from one generation of plants to
the next.
Some of the plants contained a red pigment gene taken from wild Peruvian
maize. When they were harvested last week, all their grains showed red spots
 -looking unlike any wheat grown on Earth before.
The other plants produced bacterial enzymes which the Ciba scientists
detected in simple lab tests, proving that the new genes were switched on
success-fully.
Mr David Thompson, head of research at Ciba's cereal breeding business, said
the 16 square metre trial plot yielded several kilograms of genetically
engineered wheat. The crop has been flown to the company's US research
centre in North Carolina for further analysis.
The strains were created last year in North Carolina, by shooting thousands
of microscopic gold balls coated with DNA into wheat cells.
Ciba scientists then grew two generations of plants in greenhouses before
sending the seed to Cambridgeshire for the field trial.
The UK was chosen because of the country's expertise in wheat breeding and
because Ciba sees Europe as the first market for its genetically engineered
wheat.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Ciba Seeds.
</CO>
