<HEADLINE>
FT  08 AUG 94 / UK Company News: SCI to raise offer for Great Southern
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Great Southern Group, the funerals operator which faces a hostile takeover
bid, is to receive an offer worth up to 800p a share from its US aggressor
early this week.
The offer was being thrashed out yesterday between the Field family, which
has a controlling interest in Southern, and Service Corporation
International (SCI), the world's largest funeral company.
Sources close to Houston-based SCI said yesterday that it was in talks over
an offer 'somewhere between Southern's closing share price of 709p and
800p.'
Southern was also hedging its options and holding discussions with Loewen, a
Canadian rival.
SCI made its original Pounds 87.4m offer at the start of June, but was
stonewalled by JD Field and Sons, the private company controlled by the
Field family, which has been in the burial business since 1690.
The family, said to have bridled at the abrasive approach of Mr Bill
Heiligbrodt, SCI's Texan chairman, rejected the offer immediately. It also
ignored a higher offer of 680p a share made last week, valuing the company
at Pounds 99.1m.
Under Takeover Panel rules a move has to be made this week and it is
believed that the latest offer will be accepted.
SCI controls almost 30 per cent of the enlarged capital.
</TEXT>
