<HEADLINE>
FT  08 AUG 94 / Railtrack urges staff to increase pressure on RMT to stop
strikes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Railtrack is appealing directly today to all its 12,000 employees, urging
them to contact the RMT transport union to demand the suspension of a
planned 72 hours of disruption by signalling staff.
The strikes are due to start at midnight on Thursday, affecting Friday, and
continue next Monday and Tuesday. Saturday and Sunday services should run
normally.
The state-owned company that runs the network also urged the RMT leadership
to reballot its signalling staff on the latest pay productivity offer. The
move was designed to increase the pressure on the union's executive to
return to talks to end the dispute, now entering its ninth week.
Railtrack's bulletin to all its staff asks them to call the union's London
headquarters to express their views. It said: 'Let us have a negotiated
settlement to end the dispute. We have made a commitment to negotiate until
we reach a settlement. Will the union do the same? Ask them.'
The RMT transport union executive committee is being urged by the union's
full-time officials today to consider reopening negotiations with Railtrack.
The officials believe they have won enough clarification from Railtrack on
its present offer to suggest an improvement can be made immediately in the
basic pay rates of the staff through a consolidation of half the proposed 6
per cent supplement that is already on the table.
This would be in addition to a proposed earnings rise, backdated to April 4,
of 7.2 per cent composed of a productivity-linked increase of up to 4.7 per
cent on top of a 2.5 per cent basic pay rise already agreed.
The possibility of a return to talks was glimpsed on Friday when Railtrack
chairman Mr Bob Horton suggested that the company's pay restructuring
package for signalling staff could be reshaped.
He suggested consolidating into basic rates for overtime and shift premiums
some of the proposed 6 per cent supplement.
Railtrack, however, has still not put this proposal into writing. The RMT
executive might expect to have formal confirmation on the proposed
consolidation before going back to the conciliation service Acas.
But Railtrack's appeal today, and its behaviour over the past few days since
the RMT's signalling supervisors rejected joining in the dispute after a
decisive ballot vote, suggests the company is ready to be flexible.
'There are grounds to go forward,' says today's bulletin to Railtrack staff.
As well as the immediate 7.2 per cent increase, Railtrack said last night
that the offer also involves a final restructuring deal by October involving
a further rise, plus improved holidays and sick pay.
In addition, some Pounds 50m has been put aside in the railways pension fund
to meet the cost of the increased pension benefits the signalling staff can
expect to gain if the final settlement is agreed by October 1.
</TEXT>
