<HEADLINE>
FT  08 AUG 94 / The Lex Column: Ireland
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Having won its third consecutive Eurovision song contest Ireland may be
heading for another award this year - fastest growing European economy. The
Irish government has just increased its 1994 growth forecast to a racy 5 per
cent and judging by last week's figures from AIB the optimism looks
well-founded. These showed the bank's Irish loans growing at an annualised
rate of 10 per cent in the first half while across the Irish Sea, NatWest's
loan book was down.
Not everything in Ireland is rosy. Unemployment is still very high though
this at least adds to the confidence that the economy can combine such
growth with continued low inflation. So confident are some independent
forecasters that they predict this benign environment will last to the end
of the century.
The implications have not been lost on domestic or international investors
who pushed the Dublin stock market up by 54 per cent last year. However,
this could be seen largely as a correction for the steep fall over the
previous two years and with the market 12 per cent off this year's high it
is not highly rated by international standards. The biggest problem for
investors is the limited range of stocks to choose from. Most quoted Irish
companies are either very small or, like Jefferson Smurfit, very
international. The one large industrial group that has significant exposure
to Ireland is building materials group CRH, whose shares now discount much
of the good news. Nor have investors overlooked the two banks, AIB and Bank
of Ireland, which generate half their profits in their home market. But
their shares remain modestly rated compared with their UK banks, operating
in a much more difficult climate.
</TEXT>
