<HEADLINE>
FT  08 AUG 94 / The Lex Column: European chemicals
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Half-year results from the German chemicals giants, starting next week,
should confirm that European recovery has come earlier than even bulls of
the sector dared hope. ICI and DSM have already reported volume gains
running into double digits by the end of second quarter. Although selling
prices are not much higher than this time last year, the upwards trend from
the trough reached in the final months of 1993 is clear. With capacity
utilisation rates already pushing towards 90 per cent in some areas, there
are surely further pricing gains to come.
This is good news for this year's profits. In addition to strong volume
gains through the first half of the year, the usual third quarter lull in
activity has failed to materialise. But the broader question is whether the
peak in chemicals industry profits will come sooner or last longer than
investors hitherto expected. The recent growth trend gives grounds for
optimism on the first count - barring an unforeseen event such as an oil
shock.
How long the peak lasts depends on the industry's ability to resist
investing in excess capacity during the upswing. But big capital programmes
announced this year or next would take some years to complete. If the
profits peak comes in 1996-97, there could be at least a short plateau
rather than an immediate downswing. The big European chemicals companies
have been outperforming their local stock markets for about a year on
expectations of a slow, sluggish recovery. Given the quickening pace of the
upturn it would be extraordinary if they now fell behind.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>XGZ  Europe.
</CN>
