<HEADLINE>
FT  08 AUG 94 / The Lex Column: Shady side of the street
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street is caught between a rock and a hard place. Economic indicators
which point to continued strong growth - such as last Friday's employment
data - drive shares lower on the grounds that the Federal Reserve is more
likely to raise interest rates. This week's producer and consumer price
figures could be crucial. Gathering inflation, combined with the apparent
strength of the labour market, would surely tilt the Fed towards higher
rates at its Open Market Committee meeting on August 16.
Yet pointers towards a significant slow-down in the second half of the year
 -such as lower housing starts, car sales and weaker money growth  - raise
fears that earnings expectations are too high. After the exceptionally
strong second quarter figures reported by many US companies, that might seem
an unlikely prospect. With many analysts again lifting forecasts for this
year and next, though, there is plenty of room for disappointment. The worst
of all possible worlds would be another half-point rise in rates just as it
becomes clear that the economy is already slowing.
It is always possible that the Fed will stay its hand and that growth will
fall gently back towards trend, around 2.5 per cent. Under this golden
scenario earnings estimates might turn out to be a touch optimistic, but a
stable bond market would underpin equities. While this rosy prospect helped
equities climb by 3 per cent last month, the outcome is delicately poised
and the evidence conflicting. The course of events is rarely as neat in
practice.
</TEXT>
