<HEADLINE>
FT  08 AUG 94 / Arts: Openings
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
PESARO
The annual Rossini festival in this exquisite walled town on the Adriatic
opens on Thursday with a new production of L'Italiana in Algeri. Roger
Norrington makes his Pesaro debut conducting a revival of Semiramide, and
Graham Vick joins forces with Carlo Rizzi for a staging of L'inganno felice,
the only rarity this year.
EDINBURGH
After winning an international reputation overseas, the Scottish conductor
Donald Runnicles returns home to open this year's festival with a
performance of Mahler's massive Eighth Symphony. The Edinburgh Festival
Theatre has at last become a reality and the festival is celebrating with
two wildly contrasting composers of the year, Beethoven and Chabrier.
SCOTALAND: NATIONAL GALLERY
'Monet to Matisse: Landscape Painting in France, 1874-1914' opens at the
National Gallery of Scotland on Thursday. This is one of the most ambitious
exhibitions mounted by the Gallery, ranging from the famous to lesser known
artists like Devambex, who took advantage of the bi-plane to produce one of
the first aerial paintings of the countryside.
INNSBRUCK
Best known as a ski centre, this Austrian town is developing a parallel
reputation for its summer baroque and early music festival which takes place
in region's historic buildings. This year's festival, opening on Sunday,
celebrates the 350th anniversary of Heinrich Biber, the 17th century
Bohemian composer who worked in Salzburg.
LONDON THEATRE
Opening at the Greenwhich Theatre on Monday is the recent New York hit The
Sisters Rosenweig, by Wendy Wasserstein. This British production, directed
by Michael Blakemore, stars Maureen Lipman, Janet Suzman and Lynda
Bellingham.
BRECON JAZZ
The beard and beret set head for the hills at the weekend for Brecon Jazz,
the most convivial of music festivals. Benny Carter and Slide Hampton are
the main attractions, but there's plenty of atmosphere in the side streets
and smaller venues of the Welsh market town
</TEXT>
